## The Communication That Closes the Authorization Loop

Day 95 completed the POA&M section — the commitments-tracking instrument that tells the AO how the organization has managed its security obligations over time. The POA&M's history (5 items closed, 4 items opened through monitoring, 1 Moderate finding self-identified through proactive self-assessment) tells the authorization story: an organization that identifies its own gaps, closes them at a pace that keeps up with new discoveries, and maintains AO visibility into items requiring executive attention.

Day 96 is about the communication that puts all of that work in front of the decision-maker who authorized it. The annual AO briefing is the culminating communication of the first authorization year — it synthesizes everything the nine capstone sections contain and presents it in the form the AO needs to make one decision: does the authorization remain appropriate for the second year of the three-year authorization period?

I also want to be direct about what Day 96 is not. It is not a slide deck designed to impress a non-technical executive by claiming "85% risk reduction" or "all critical issues resolved." That framing would be dishonest — two risks are currently rated HIGH (RS-001 credential theft, RS-004 ransomware), one authorization condition is AT RISK, and the program's most significant control gap (AU-12) was self-identified during the year and is in active remediation. The executive communication that serves the organization is the one that presents this picture accurately, with the professional judgment and clear recommendations that the AO needs to make an informed decision.

The Day 85 communication principle applies here with full force: the ISSO's job is decision support, not information transfer. The AO's decision is whether to continue authorization. The communication should provide exactly the information that supports that decision, organized to make the decision clear.

