## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The value of honest executive communication — specifically presenting gaps accurately rather than managing the appearance of compliance success — is validated by the **2020 Zoom security disclosures**.

When security researchers identified several significant security issues with Zoom during the pandemic surge (false end-to-end encryption claims, meeting ID vulnerabilities, data routing through China), Zoom's initial public communications downplayed the issues. When the full picture became clear through independent research, the credibility gap between what Zoom had communicated and what was actually true became a larger organizational problem than the technical vulnerabilities themselves.

The Zoom case is not a GRC failure in the traditional sense — it is a communication failure that created a credibility problem. For the OpenMRS program, the equivalent risk is an annual AO briefing that presents "85% risk reduction — all critical issues resolved" when two risks are currently HIGH-rated and one authorization condition is AT RISK. If the AO later discovers that the briefing overstated the program's posture, the credibility of every subsequent ISSO communication is reduced.

Honest communication is not just ethically correct. It is strategically correct — the ISSO who presents gaps accurately, with remediation plans and specific asks, builds the kind of AO relationship where the AO is a genuine governance partner rather than an authority figure to be managed.

